On January 12, 2018, President Trump signed legislation designating the Martin Luther King, Jr. National Historic Site as a National Historic Park. The new law expands the protected area and honors Dr. King's legacy. During a ceremony at the White House, President Trump spoke about Dr. King's life and his impact on civil rights. He emphasized the importance of equality and urged Americans to observe Martin Luther King, Jr. Federal Holiday with acts of civic work and community service. Secretary Carson also delivered remarks, highlighting Dr. King's message of equality, justice, and human dignity. Pastor Isaac Newton Farris, Jr., the nephew of Dr. King, spoke about the significance of the holiday as a day of service and unity. The ceremony concluded with President Trump signing the proclamation for the Martin Luther King, Jr. Federal Holiday.